# Fixture: fm5-base-mid-query
# Finding: Failure Mode 5 — BASE declaration inside WHERE clause (INVALID)
# Spec: SPARQL 1.1 §3.1; grammar production Prologue ::= (BaseDecl | PrefixDecl)*
#
# Hypothesis: SPARQL 1.1 §3.1 restricts BASE to the Prologue, which appears
# before the query form keyword (SELECT/CONSTRUCT/ASK/DESCRIBE). A BASE
# declaration inside a WHERE clause is a grammar violation. Correct
# implementations MUST reject this with a parse error.
#
# Divergence: An implementation that reuses the Turtle parser's IRI
# resolution logic may silently accept BASE inside a group graph pattern
# and apply the second base IRI to subsequent relative IRIs, producing
# wrong IRI resolution without error. This is a real accept/reject split.
# Expected grammar-level behaviour: PARSE ERROR (reject).

BASE <http://example/a/>
SELECT * WHERE {
  <foo> <http://example/p> ?o .
  BASE <http://example/b/>
  <bar> ?q ?r .
}
